## Medical Procedures and Drugs Used in Euthanasia

### Administration Methods

Euthanasia is typically performed through the administration of lethal drugs, most commonly via intravenous injection. In veterinary practice, intraorgan or intraperitoneal injections are also used, but human euthanasia protocols prioritize intravenous routes for rapid and painless effect ([CliniciansBrief](https://www.cliniciansbrief.com/article/euthanasia-protocols)).

### Drug Protocols

The drugs used in euthanasia are selected for their ability to induce unconsciousness rapidly, followed by cessation of vital functions without pain or distress. The typical protocol involves:

1. **Sedatives or Anesthetics:** Barbiturates (e.g., pentobarbital, secobarbital) or hypnotics (e.g., propofol) are administered first to induce unconsciousness and prevent pain or anxiety ([PMC9270985](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9270985/); [ABC News](https://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-10-20/assisted-dying-what-is-need-from-drugs-for-voluntary-euthanasia/9069896)).

2. **Neuromuscular Blocking Agents:** These drugs (e.g., pancuronium, rocuronium) cause paralysis of all striated muscles, including respiratory muscles, leading to respiratory arrest ([PMC9270985](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9270985/)).

3. **Cardiotoxic Agents:** In some protocols, potassium chloride or digoxin may be used to induce cardiac arrest, although these are less common due to potential distress if consciousness is not fully suppressed ([PMC9270985](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9270985/)).

### Oral Administration

In physician-assisted suicide, oral ingestion of lethal medications such as barbiturates is common. Patients self-administer these drugs, which typically induce coma followed by death within minutes to hours ([Death with Dignity FAQ](https://deathwithdignity.org/resources/faqs/); [CliniciansBrief](https://www.cliniciansbrief.com/article/euthanasia-protocols)).

### Dosages

Dosages vary depending on the drug and patient factors. For example, pentobarbital doses can range from 1 to 15 grams intravenously for euthanasia purposes. Oral doses for assisted suicide are higher (e.g., 255 mg/kg) to ensure lethality ([PMC9270985](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9270985/); [CliniciansBrief](https://www.cliniciansbrief.com/article/euthanasia-protocols)).

